					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The Zapper can detect light at any time. It's just that the light needs to be strobing at 15.7 kHz the way it does on a CRT, and I don't think LCDs and plasmas do that. I've pointed my Zapper at an LCD while running the Zapper test program Zap Ruder, and it registered the same way as if it weren't pointed at the screen at all. Even strobing an LED backlight at 15.7 kHz wouldn't help with games like Operation Wolf and ZapPing that not only need 15.7 kHz but also depend on the top-to-bottom scanning order, as they time from the top of the screen to when the sensor registers light.</div>

